EZEK_CONTEXT = {
  "1": {
    "1": "<p>Ezekiel was a priest who was deported to Babylon in the first deportation (597 BCE) and received his call-vision in 593 BCE by the Chebar canal in Babylonia ('the thirtieth year', 1:1 — possibly his own thirtieth year, the age for priestly service). He prophesied to the exilic community ca. 593-571 BCE. His priestly background shapes his theology: the book is preoccupied with divine glory (<em>kavod</em>), the departure of the Shekinah from the temple (chs. 8-11), and its eschatological return (chs. 40-48). The merkabah vision (ch. 1) was the most influential single vision in subsequent Jewish mysticism — the Hekhalot literature built an entire tradition of heavenly ascent around it. The four living creatures (lion, ox, eagle, human) reappear in Irenaeus's identification of the four Gospel symbols.</p>"
  },
  "37": {
    "1": "<p>The valley of dry bones vision (37:1-14) is addressed to the exilic community that had concluded 'our bones are dried up, our hope is lost, we are indeed cut off' (v. 11). The corporate resurrection metaphor — national restoration envisioned as bodily resurrection — uses the imagery of physical resurrection for Israel's return from exile. This is not a straightforward prophecy of individual eschatological resurrection (though the same imagery is applied there in Isa 26:19; Dan 12:2), but a bold use of resurrection as the metaphor for what only divine creative power could accomplish for the exiled nation. The NT develops the resurrection-from-exile typology: Christ's resurrection is both personal and the beginning of the great return-from-death that Ezekiel envisioned.</p>"
  }
}

EZEK_CHRIST = {
  "29": {
    "1": "<p>A structural note: The date formula places this oracle in January 587 BCE — the tenth year, tenth month, twelfth day, during the final siege of Jerusalem. The Christological backdrop: the nations surrounding Israel — Egypt, Tyre, Edom, Moab, Ammon — are all judged in Ezekiel 25–32, clearing the way for YHWH's restoration of his people. Every national judgment oracle in the prophets points toward the day when all powers hostile to YHWH's kingdom will be broken and Christ will reign over all (Rev 11:15).</p>",
    "2": "<p>A structural note: 'Son of man, set your face against Pharaoh king of Egypt and prophesy against him.' The prophetic commissioning sets Ezekiel as YHWH's spokesperson against the world's greatest empire. Christ commissions his apostles with the same authority in reverse: not &ldquo;prophesy against&rdquo; but &ldquo;proclaim the gospel to every nation&rdquo; (Matt 28:19). The apostolic mission is the positive counterpart to the prophetic-judgment commission, both proceeding from the divine throne.</p>",
    "3": "<p>A type: 'Behold I am against you, Pharaoh king of Egypt, the great dragon that lies in the midst of his streams, who says, My Nile is my own; I made it for myself.' The great dragon (<em>tannin gadol</em>) who claims self-creation is the recurring anti-type of every power that displaces YHWH. The dragon imagery runs from Genesis and Exodus through Ezekiel into Revelation's great red dragon (Rev 12:3) and the beast from the sea (Rev 13:1). Christ's victory over the dragon at the cross (Col 2:15; Rev 12:11) is the eschatological counterpart: every earthly power that claims self-creation and self-sovereignty is judged by the one who actually created all things.</p>",
    "4": "<p>A pattern: 'And I will put hooks in your jaws and make the fish of your streams stick to your scales and I will draw you up out of the midst of your streams.' YHWH's sovereignty over the great dragon is expressed through fishing imagery — the hook, the net, the dragging out. God is never the one caught; the powers that oppose him are always the ones netted. This pattern culminates in Revelation: the beast and false prophet are captured and thrown into the lake of fire (Rev 19:20). Christ's binding of the strong man (Matt 12:29) is the inaugurated form of the final binding of the great dragon.</p>",
    "5": "<p>A pattern: 'And I will cast you out into the wilderness, you and all the fish of your streams; you shall fall on the open field and not be brought together or gathered. To the beasts of the earth and to the birds of the heavens I have given you as food.' The great dragon not just defeated but devoured — stripped of dignity and abandoned to scavengers. This is the pattern of Rev 19:17-18: the great supper of God where the birds feast on the flesh of kings and captains. The humiliation of power is complete. Christ's resurrection is the reverse pattern: the one who was killed did not remain in the grave but was raised and glorified.</p>",
    "6": "<p>A type: 'Then all the inhabitants of Egypt shall know that I am YHWH, because they have been a staff of reed to the house of Israel.' Egypt as the broken reed (<em>qaneh</em>) is one of the OT's primary anti-types for false security. Isaiah 36:6 uses the same image: the Rabshakeh taunts Judah, &ldquo;Behold you are relying on Egypt, that broken reed of a staff which will pierce the hand of any man who leans on it.&rdquo; Christ is the true staff — &ldquo;thy rod and thy staff they comfort me&rdquo; (Ps 23:4). Every broken reed is an invitation to find the one who will not break.</p>",
    "7": "<p>A pattern: 'When they grasped you with the hand, you broke and tore all their shoulders; and when they leaned on you, you broke and made all their loins to shake.' The broken reed pierces and tears — the thing Israel leaned on for strength became the source of injury. The pattern is inverted in the NT: Christ is the one who bears our burdens and gives rest to the weary (Matt 11:28-30). The yoke he offers is easy and his burden is light — the complete antithesis of the Egypt-reed that punctures the hand of anyone who leans on it.</p>",
    "8": "<p>A pattern: 'Therefore thus says the Lord GOD: Behold I will bring a sword upon you and will cut off from you man and beast.' The sword of divine judgment is wielded by YHWH himself — Egypt's fall is not random military misfortune but divine verdict. This pattern points toward Christ as the one who comes with the sharp two-edged sword from his mouth (Rev 1:16; 19:15). Every national judgment oracle in the prophets is a proleptic form of the final judgment that Christ will execute.</p>",
    "9": "<p>A direct revelation: 'And the land of Egypt shall be a desolation and a waste. Then they will know that I am YHWH — because he said, The Nile is mine and I made it.' The judgment's purpose is revelation: <em>yad&apos;u ki-ani YHWH</em>, they shall know that I am YHWH. The fundamental sin judged is not military alliance but the claim to self-creation. In Christ, the Creator becomes a creature (John 1:14) — not to abdicate his creative authority but to restore what the creature's rebellion had broken. The recognition formula finds its fullest expression in Phil 2:10-11: every knee shall bow and every tongue confess that Jesus Christ is Lord.</p>",
    "10": "<p>A structural note: 'I am against you and against your streams and I will make the land of Egypt an utter waste and desolation from Migdol to Syene, as far as the border of Cush.' Migdol (northeastern border) to Syene (modern Aswan, southern boundary) designates all of Egypt. The scope of judgment matches the scope of Pharaoh's claims: he claimed the whole Nile, so the whole land is judged. This geographic totality points toward the equally universal scope of Christ's final judgment: &ldquo;all nations shall be gathered before him&rdquo; (Matt 25:32).</p>",
    "11": "<p>A structural note: 'No foot of man shall pass through it and no foot of beast shall pass through it; it shall be uninhabited forty years.' The forty-year desolation echoes Israel's forty years in the wilderness — the period of purification and transformation. The number forty consistently signals testing and transition (Moses on Sinai, Israel in the desert, Jesus in the wilderness). Egypt will undergo the same wilderness-period it imposed on Israel. What Egypt inflicted, it now experiences — the lex talionis of divine history.</p>",
    "12": "<p>A structural note: 'And I will scatter the Egyptians among the nations and disperse them through the countries.' Egypt scattered among the nations is the reverse of Israel's exile to Egypt. In Genesis, Jacob's family went down to Egypt for refuge; now Egypt is scattered as Israel had been. The dispersal-judgment that fell on Israel for covenant infidelity falls on Egypt for its anti-covenantal role. Every nation that is used to oppress YHWH's people faces the same scattering that his people experienced.</p>",
    "13": "<p>A pattern: 'For thus says the Lord GOD: At the end of forty years I will gather the Egyptians from the peoples among whom they were scattered.' The gathering after scattering is the pattern of divine restoration running throughout Ezekiel (chs 36–37). After judgment comes the ingathering. This pattern points toward the final gathering that Christ enacts: &ldquo;the Son of Man will send his angels and they will gather his elect from the four winds&rdquo; (Matt 24:31). Even Egypt — the paradigmatic oppressor — is gathered and restored, demonstrating that YHWH's purpose is always ultimately restorative, not merely punitive.</p>",
    "14": "<p>A pattern: 'And I will restore the fortunes of Egypt and bring them back to the land of Pathros, the land of their origin, and there they shall be a lowly kingdom.' Egypt restored to Pathros and made a lowly kingdom: the proud empire humbled to its beginnings. The pattern of humiliation-and-restoration is the crucifixion-resurrection shape of divine history. Egypt goes from empire to lowly kingdom — from Pharaoh's self-declared greatness to a modest, chastened state. What the cross does to human pride is what YHWH does here to Egypt: it is not destroyed but reconfigured.</p>",
    "15": "<p>A pattern: 'It shall be the most lowly of the kingdoms and never again exalt itself above the nations.' Never again will Egypt exalt itself — the proud empire is permanently humbled. This is the beatitude pattern of Christ's kingdom: &ldquo;the meek shall inherit the earth&rdquo; (Matt 5:5); &ldquo;whoever exalts himself will be humbled and whoever humbles himself will be exalted&rdquo; (Matt 23:12). The humbling of Egypt is not revenge but the reordering of all things under YHWH's kingdom — preparation for the world in which the lowly are the great.</p>",
    "16": "<p>A direct revelation: 'And it shall never again be the confidence of the house of Israel, recalling their iniquity when they turn to them for aid. Then they will know that I am YHWH.' YHWH removes Egypt as a false confidence precisely so that Israel will look to him alone. Every broken prop — every failed alliance, every collapsed human institution — is YHWH's invitation to find confidence in him. Paul's &ldquo;such is the confidence that we have through Christ toward God&rdquo; (2 Cor 3:4) is the NT voice of a people for whom Egypt has finally been removed as an option.</p>",
    "17": "<p>A structural note: 'In the twenty-seventh year in the first month on the first day of the month the word of YHWH came to me.' This date — 571 BCE — is the latest of all Ezekiel's dated oracles, seventeen years after the first Egypt oracle (29:1). The oracles against Egypt span Ezekiel's entire prophetic ministry, suggesting that Egypt is not a peripheral concern but a structural feature of his vision: the great world-power that embodied opposition to YHWH's purposes must be comprehensively judged before the new creation can emerge.</p>",
    "18": "<p>A structural note: 'Son of man, Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon made his army labor hard against Tyre. Every head was made bald and every shoulder was rubbed bare, yet neither he nor his army got anything from Tyre as wages for the labor he had performed against it.' Nebuchadnezzar's unsuccessful siege of Tyre left his army with nothing. YHWH's compensation: Egypt will be given as wages. This divine economy — where human instruments of judgment receive divine compensation — shows YHWH's sovereign management of history. Christ as the one &ldquo;through whom and for whom all things were created&rdquo; (Col 1:16) is the one who assigns historical outcomes.</p>",
    "19": "<p>A pattern: 'Therefore thus says the Lord GOD: Behold I will give the land of Egypt to Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon; and he shall carry off its wealth and despoil it and plunder it; and it shall be the wages for his army.' Nebuchadnezzar as YHWH's instrument of judgment against Egypt demonstrates that YHWH's sovereignty extends over all nations, not just Israel. The NT expands this: Pilate has no authority except what is given from above (John 19:11); even the Roman empire that crucified Jesus was an instrument used within YHWH's purposes, and the cross — the apparent defeat — was the decisive victory.</p>",
    "20": "<p>A pattern: 'I have given him the land of Egypt as his payment for which he labored, because they worked for me, declares the Lord GOD.' Nebuchadnezzar &ldquo;worked for me&rdquo; — the foreign king, unknowing, served YHWH's purposes. This is the pattern of the Joseph narrative (Gen 50:20: you intended evil, but God intended it for good) and of the cross: those who crucified Christ were doing what God's hand had predestined to take place (Acts 4:28), and the act intended for evil became the source of universal salvation.</p>",
    "21": "<p>A direct revelation: 'On that day I will cause a horn to spring up for the house of Israel, and I will open your lips among them. Then they will know that I am YHWH.' The &ldquo;horn&rdquo; (<em>qeren</em>) is the standard OT symbol for messianic power (Ps 132:17: &ldquo;there I will make a horn to spring up for David&rdquo;). Zechariah's Benedictus draws on exactly this language: &ldquo;He has raised up a horn of salvation for us in the house of his servant David&rdquo; (Luke 1:69). The oracle against Egypt closes with a messianic note: Israel's salvation is the positive purpose behind Egypt's judgment. Egypt's judgment and the Messiah's horn are the two sides of YHWH's eschatological program.</p>"
  },
  "30": {
    "1": "<p>A structural note: This oracle (30:1-19) is undated, suggesting a more universal application: unlike the dated oracles tied to specific historical moments, this oracle proclaims the cosmic principle that YHWH's judgment against all powers hostile to his people is coming — a principle that transcends any single historical fulfillment. The absence of a date makes it permanently applicable.</p>",
    "2": "<p>A pattern: '&ldquo;Wail, Alas for the day!&rdquo; For the day is near.' The prophetic wail (<em>yelalah</em>) is the lamentation form used when announcing judgment. The very form of the proclamation — a lament over what is coming — shows YHWH's grief in judgment. This pattern points toward Christ's own lamentation over Jerusalem (Luke 19:41-44; Matt 23:37-38): the one who pronounces judgment weeps over those being judged. Divine judgment is never celebrated; it is always accompanied by divine grief.</p>",
    "3": "<p>A direct revelation: 'For the day is near, the day of YHWH is near; it will be a day of clouds, a time of doom for the nations.' The Day of YHWH (<em>yom YHWH</em>) is the prophets' term for the decisive intervention of the divine king to judge his enemies and vindicate his people. In the NT, the Day of the Lord is the parousia of Christ: &ldquo;the day of the Lord will come like a thief in the night&rdquo; (1 Thess 5:2). Every prophetic Day of YHWH oracle is a type of the final Day when Christ appears and every enemy of his kingdom is permanently subdued.</p>",
    "4": "<p>A pattern: 'A sword shall come upon Egypt and anguish shall be in Cush when the slain fall in Egypt and her wealth is carried away and her foundations are torn down.' The judgment of the center spreads to the periphery. When Egypt was great, she blessed her allies; when she falls, they fall with her. This reverses the pattern of imperial blessing. Christ's judgment at the last day is the final anti-imperial event: every alliance with the powers of this world will be revealed as futile when the empires themselves are undone.</p>",
    "5": "<p>A structural note: 'Cush and Put and Lud and all Arabia and Libya and the people of the land that is in league shall fall with them by the sword.' The list of Egypt's allied nations confirms the scope of judgment: no human alliance survives YHWH's judgment. The network of nations that seemed impregnable dissolves. The contrast is Christ's kingdom alone, which endures: &ldquo;all authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me&rdquo; (Matt 28:18).</p>",
    "6": "<p>A pattern: 'Thus says YHWH: Those who support Egypt shall fall and her proud might shall come down; from Migdol to Syene they shall fall within her by the sword.' Those whose security rests on Egypt's power fall when Egypt falls. The pattern warns against building one's security on any human power. Christ alone is the rock that cannot be moved (Matt 7:24-25): building on him means that when all else falls, the one who trusts in him stands.</p>",
    "7": "<p>A structural note: 'And they shall be desolate in the midst of desolate countries and their cities shall be in the midst of cities that are laid waste.' Egypt's desolation placed in the broader context of widespread devastation — the particular judgment of Egypt is part of the comprehensive ruin of all the nations that opposed YHWH's purposes. This comprehensive desolation points forward to the &ldquo;passing away of the old heaven and old earth&rdquo; (Rev 21:1) before the new creation emerges.</p>",
    "8": "<p>A direct revelation: 'Then they will know that I am YHWH when I put fire on Egypt and all her helpers are broken.' Fire on Egypt and the recognition formula. The fire of Sinai and the fire of judgment are both revelatory — YHWH revealing himself through fire as he is. Christ is the one who &ldquo;will baptize with the Holy Spirit and fire&rdquo; (Matt 3:11): his Spirit-fire is the redemptive form of the same divine fire that Ezekiel sees falling on Egypt.</p>",
    "9": "<p>A pattern: 'On that day messengers shall go out from me in ships to terrify the unsuspecting people of Cush, and anguish shall come upon them on the day of Egypt's doom; for behold it is coming.' Messengers going forth on ships to announce judgment to the nations — the geography of proclamation. In the NT, messengers go out not to announce judgment but the gospel; yet both commissions proceed from the same divine throne. The apostolic mission is the eschatological answer to the prophetic-judgment dispatch: instead of terror, the messengers bring peace through Christ.</p>",
    "10": "<p>A pattern: 'Thus says the Lord GOD: I will put an end to the wealth of Egypt by the hand of Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon.' The end of Egypt's wealth by human hand — yet YHWH's hand working through Nebuchadnezzar. The same double agency appears at the cross: Pilate, Herod, and the Sanhedrin acted by human decision; yet &ldquo;this Jesus was delivered up according to the definite plan and foreknowledge of God&rdquo; (Acts 2:23). Human agency and divine sovereignty are not opposed in Ezekiel's or the NT's vision of history.</p>",
    "11": "<p>A structural note: 'He and his people with him, the most ruthless of nations, shall be brought in to destroy the land; and they shall draw their swords against Egypt and fill the land with the slain.' YHWH uses even the most violent human instruments to execute judgment. This is not an endorsement of Babylonian cruelty but a statement about divine sovereignty: no human wickedness falls outside YHWH's governance, and the very ruthlessness of the instrument magnifies the justice of the judgment against those who could only be moved by such force.</p>",
    "12": "<p>A structural note: 'And I will dry up the Nile and will sell the land into the hand of evildoers; I will bring desolation upon the land and everything in it by the hand of foreigners; I am YHWH; I have spoken.' &ldquo;I am YHWH; I have spoken&rdquo; — the divine self-identification as guarantor of the word. YHWH's word is certain because of who YHWH is. Christ extends this guarantee: &ldquo;Heaven and earth will pass away, but my words will not pass away&rdquo; (Matt 24:35). The divine word that pledged Egypt's judgment is the same word that pledges the final restoration of all things.</p>",
    "13": "<p>A pattern: 'Thus says the Lord GOD: I will destroy the idols and put an end to the images in Memphis; there shall no longer be a prince from the land of Egypt; so I will put fear in the land of Egypt.' The destruction of idols as part of national judgment is the pattern that culminates in Christ's demolition of all idol-worship: &ldquo;flee from idolatry&rdquo; (1 Cor 10:14). Every prophecy of idol-destruction is a partial anticipation of the day when &ldquo;the idols shall utterly pass away&rdquo; (Isa 2:18).</p>",
    "14": "<p>A structural note: 'I will make Pathros a desolation and will set fire to Zoan and will execute judgments on Thebes.' The three historic capitals of Egypt — Pathros (Upper Egypt), Zoan (Tanis, the Delta), and Thebes (Karnak/Luxor, the religious center) — are all under judgment. The destruction of Egypt's sacred centers is YHWH declaring his supremacy over every human rival to his glory. When the old religious centers of the world's empires are gone, the city of God alone remains (Rev 21).</p>",
    "15": "<p>A structural note: 'And I will pour out my wrath on Pelusium the stronghold of Egypt and cut off the multitude of Thebes.' Pelusium was Egypt's northeastern military fortress — the gateway city controlling access from the land route. YHWH's wrath poured on the military stronghold signals that even the strongest fortification cannot withstand divine judgment. The NT applies this spiritually: &ldquo;the weapons of our warfare are not of the flesh but have divine power to destroy strongholds&rdquo; (2 Cor 10:4). Christ's resurrection demolished the ultimate stronghold — death itself.</p>",
    "16": "<p>A structural note: 'And I will put fire on Egypt; Pelusium shall writhe in anguish; Thebes shall be breached; and Memphis shall have distress daily.' The sequential judgment of Egypt's great cities — fortress, temple-capital, administrative center — shows systematic dismantling. YHWH does not judge randomly; he dismantles the structures of human power methodically. This systematic quality points toward the comprehensive scope of Christ's lordship: every competing authority structure, every rival claim to sovereignty, is specifically addressed and dismantled.</p>",
    "17": "<p>A structural note: 'The young men of On and of Pi-beseth shall fall by the sword, and the women shall go into captivity.' On (Heliopolis) was the center of Egyptian solar worship; Pi-beseth (Bubastis) was the center of Bast-worship. The solar and feline gods of Egypt cannot protect their devotees from YHWH's judgment. The one who made the sun is Lord over it and all else.</p>",
    "18": "<p>A pattern: 'At Tehaphnehes the day shall be dark when I break there the yoke-bars of Egypt and her proud might shall come to an end in her; she shall be covered by a cloud.' Darkness over Tehaphnehes echoes the ninth plague (darkness over all Egypt, Exod 10:21-23) and anticipates the darkness at the cross (Matt 27:45). Every darkening of sky in the prophets is a shadow of Golgotha, where the sun was darkened for three hours as the ultimate judgment fell — simultaneously the final Passover and the Egypt-judgment brought to its terrible consummation.</p>",
    "19": "<p>A direct revelation: 'Thus I will execute judgments on Egypt. Then they shall know that I am YHWH.' The recognition formula closes the section: judgments executed — knowledge of YHWH. The purpose of all divine judgment is ultimately revelatory. No nation — not Egypt, not Babylon, not Rome — can ultimately resist knowing YHWH. The final revelation toward which all these partial revelations point is Phil 2:10-11: at the name of Jesus, every knee bows and every tongue confesses Christ as Lord.</p>",
    "20": "<p>A structural note: 'In the eleventh year in the first month on the seventh day the word of YHWH came to me.' April 587 BCE — three months after the first Egypt oracle and during the siege of Jerusalem. The oracle of the broken arm of Pharaoh is given as Pharaoh Hophra's army retreats from its failed attempt to relieve Jerusalem. The historical moment: Jerusalem is about to fall; the one power that could have stopped it has failed.</p>",
    "21": "<p>A type: 'Son of man I have broken the arm of Pharaoh king of Egypt and behold it has not been bound up to heal it, to bind it with a bandage so that it may become strong to grasp the sword.' The broken arm (<em>zero&apos;a</em>) of Pharaoh is YHWH's act — and no human physician can repair what the divine hand has broken. The type inverts in Christ: YHWH strengthens the arm of the weak (Isa 40:29-31; 41:10) and specifically &ldquo;reveals his arm&rdquo; in the Servant (Isa 53:1). The broken Pharaoh-arm and the saving YHWH-arm are the same divine hand in two modes — judgment toward the proud, strength toward the humble.</p>",
    "22": "<p>A direct revelation: 'Therefore thus says the Lord GOD: Behold I am against Pharaoh king of Egypt and will break his arms, both the strong arm and the one that was broken, and I will make the sword fall from his hand.' YHWH declares himself personally &ldquo;against Pharaoh&rdquo; — the divine adversary of the king who claimed divinity. In Christ, YHWH is &ldquo;for us&rdquo; (Rom 8:31): having exhausted himself against every human Pharaoh who claimed divine sovereignty, the full force of divine hostility is expended on the powers, and nothing remains to be against those who are in Christ.</p>",
    "23": "<p>A structural note: 'And I will scatter the Egyptians among the nations and disperse them through the countries.' The scattering formula repeats from 29:12 — the diaspora of Egypt mirrors the diaspora of Israel. What Israel experienced as covenant consequence, Egypt experiences as universal judgment. The one who scatters is the one who can also gather: every scattering oracle in Ezekiel is paired with a gathering promise (34:12-13; 36:24; 37:21). The final gathering is Christ's: &ldquo;to gather into one the children of God who are scattered abroad&rdquo; (John 11:52).</p>",
    "24": "<p>A type: 'And I will strengthen the arms of the king of Babylon and put my sword in his hand, but I will break the arms of Pharaoh, and he will groan before him like a mortally wounded man.' YHWH strengthens Nebuchadnezzar's arms and breaks Pharaoh's: the divine agency giving and taking power is unmistakable. The type points toward Christ's exaltation: &ldquo;YHWH said to my Lord, sit at my right hand until I make your enemies a footstool for your feet&rdquo; (Ps 110:1). The pattern of the Father strengthening the Son and breaking his enemies is Ezekiel's Nebuchadnezzar oracle eschatologically transposed.</p>",
    "25": "<p>A direct revelation: 'When I strengthen the arms of the king of Babylon and he stretches them out against Egypt then they will know that I am YHWH. And I will scatter the Egyptians among the nations and disperse them among the countries.' The recognition formula emerges once more through Babylon's conquest. Every nation comes to know YHWH — willingly in worship (Isa 2:2-4) or forcibly through judgment (Ps 2:10-12). Christ's kingdom offers the willing-knowledge path: &ldquo;come to me, all who labor and are heavy laden&rdquo; (Matt 11:28). The moment of forced knowing at the end is the failure to accept willing knowing before the end.</p>",
    "26": "<p>A direct revelation: 'And I will scatter the Egyptians among the nations and disperse them among the countries. Then they will know that I am YHWH.' The recognition formula closes the chapter for the third time. Three-fold repetition frames the entire Day of Egypt oracle as a revelation event: judgment is not YHWH's last word about Egypt but his way of making himself known to the nations. The God who reveals himself through judgment is the same God who reveals himself through the incarnation — both are acts of self-disclosure aimed at the same end: that all shall know that YHWH, who is Jesus, is Lord.</p>"
  },
  "31": {
    "1": "<p>A structural note: 'In the eleventh year in the third month on the first day of the month the word of YHWH came to me.' June 587 BCE — one month before Jerusalem falls (July 586 BCE). Ezekiel's lament for Egypt as the great cedar is delivered at the moment when both Jerusalem and Egypt are approaching their doom. The cedar oracle (31:1-18) is one of Ezekiel's great sustained metaphors, comparable to the vine (ch 15), the eagle-and-vine (ch 17), and the dry bones (ch 37) in literary power and theological depth.</p>",
    "2": "<p>A structural note: 'Son of man, say to Pharaoh king of Egypt and to his multitude: Whom are you like in your greatness?' The rhetorical question — &ldquo;whom are you like in your greatness?&rdquo; — invites Pharaoh to compare himself to the greatest. The answer will be the cedar of Lebanon, the most majestic of trees. But the point is not admiration; it is warning: the greatest tree ever seen was cut down. No greatness is permanent under YHWH's sovereignty.</p>",
    "3": "<p>A type: 'Behold Assyria was a cedar in Lebanon with beautiful branches and forest shade, and of great height, its top among the clouds.' The cedar of Lebanon (<em>erez hallevanon</em>) is Ezekiel's image for imperial greatness. The cedar's &ldquo;top among the clouds&rdquo; echoes the Tower of Babel (Gen 11:4: &ldquo;a tower with its top in the heavens&rdquo;) — the recurring image of human ambition that reaches for the sky. Against this, Christ is the one who actually came down from the heights (John 6:38: &ldquo;I have come down from heaven&rdquo;) — true greatness that descended, not false greatness that climbed.</p>",
    "4": "<p>A pattern: 'The waters nourished it; the deep made it grow tall, making its rivers flow around the place of its planting, sending forth its streams to all the trees of the field.' The abundant nourishment of Egypt's imperial wealth — YHWH controlling those very waters (29:3). Every resource Egypt used to build its empire was ultimately YHWH's provision, diverted for imperial purposes. The parable of the talents (Matt 25:14-30) makes the same point: all human capacity is entrusted, not owned.</p>",
    "5": "<p>A pattern: 'Therefore it towered high above all the trees of the field; its boughs grew large and its branches long from abundant water in its shoots.' The cedar grew taller than all others because of its unique water supply — its greatness was circumstantial, not essential. The same circumstantial quality applies to all human greatness: nations and empires are great because of geography, resources, timing — providentially supplied advantages. The humility required is to acknowledge this, as Daniel told Nebuchadnezzar: &ldquo;the Most High God rules the kingdom of mankind and sets over it whom he will&rdquo; (Dan 5:21).</p>",
    "6": "<p>A pattern: 'All the birds of the heavens made their nests in its boughs; under its branches all the beasts of the field gave birth to their young, and under its shadow lived all great nations.' The great cedar as shelter for all creatures — the image of an imperial patron-tree. The image is reused in a positive Christological direction in the parable of the mustard seed (Matt 13:32; Mark 4:32): &ldquo;it becomes the greatest of all shrubs and becomes a tree so that the birds of the air come and make nests in its branches.&rdquo; What Egypt's cedar was in shadow-form — a tree sheltering all nations — Christ's kingdom is in final and true form.</p>",
    "7": "<p>A pattern: 'It was beautiful in its greatness, in the length of its branches; for its roots went down to abundant water.' The beauty of the cedar is genuine — YHWH made the Nile, the cedars, the great natural world that Egypt drew upon. But beauty and greatness rooted in creation, unacknowledged as gift, become pride. The pattern warns that even genuine beauty becomes disordered when it is self-referential rather than doxological. Christ is the true beauty that does not become disordered: &ldquo;full of grace and truth&rdquo; (John 1:14).</p>",
    "8": "<p>A pattern: 'The cedars in the garden of God could not rival it, nor the fir trees equal its boughs; neither were the plane trees like its branches; no tree in the garden of God was its equal in beauty.' &ldquo;The garden of God&rdquo; — Eden — is the standard of comparison. The cosmic hyperbole positions Egypt as the greatest power in creation's entire history, setting up the judgment: if not even Eden's trees compare to this cedar, what can topple it? Only YHWH himself. The same logic applies to every claim to ultimate greatness: Christ alone exceeds all.</p>",
    "9": "<p>A pattern: 'I made it beautiful in the mass of its branches, and all the trees of Eden envied it that were in the garden of God.' &ldquo;I made it beautiful&rdquo; — YHWH takes credit for the cedar's beauty. Egypt's greatness was YHWH's creation, making its pride all the more inexcusable: the very beauty it turned into an idol was given by the one it displaced. Paul's &ldquo;what do you have that you did not receive? If then you received it, why do you boast as if you did not receive it?&rdquo; (1 Cor 4:7) is the NT expression of the same principle.</p>",
    "10": "<p>A direct revelation: 'Therefore thus says the Lord GOD: Because it towered high and set its top among the clouds and its heart was proud of its height, I will give it into the hand of a mighty one of the nations.' The heart was proud of its height (<em>gavah libbo begobho</em>) — pride rooted not in false claims but in genuine greatness turned inward. Christ's teaching makes the same principle explicit: &ldquo;Everyone who exalts himself will be humbled&rdquo; (Luke 14:11). The inevitable, universal law of divine governance: pride precedes the fall, without exception. The cedar fell; Babylon fell; Rome fell; every proud empire falls. Christ alone — the humble one — is exalted permanently.</p>",
    "11": "<p>A pattern: 'He dealt with it as its wickedness deserved; and a mighty one of the nations cut it down and left it.' The cedar &ldquo;dealt with as its wickedness deserved&rdquo; — the lex talionis of cosmic history. All wickedness receives its due; no proud empire escapes its accounting. This is the bedrock of the prophetic vision: history is not chaos but moral governance. Christ is the judge before whose throne all accounting is made final (Rev 20:12-13).</p>",
    "12": "<p>A structural note: 'Foreigners, the most ruthless of nations, have cut it down and left it. On the mountains and in all the valleys its branches have fallen and its boughs are broken in all the ravines of the land, and all the peoples of the earth have gone away from its shadow and left it.' The cedar falls and all who sheltered in it flee — the empire's collapse leaves its dependents exposed. Only the one who shelters in YHWH is safe when empires fall (Ps 46:1-3: &ldquo;God is our refuge and strength, a very present help in trouble. Therefore we will not fear though the earth gives way&rdquo;).</p>",
    "13": "<p>A structural note: 'On its fallen trunk all the birds of the heavens settled, and on its branches all the beasts of the field took shelter.' The same birds and beasts that nested in the living cedar now dwell on the dead trunk. What was life-giving shelter has become a resting place for scavengers. The scavengers on the dead cedar echo the great feast of judgment (Rev 19:17-18; Ezek 39:17-20). The contrast with Christ's resurrection is stark: his body did not see corruption (Acts 2:27, citing Ps 16:10).</p>",
    "14": "<p>A direct revelation: 'This is in order that no trees by the waters may grow to towering height or set their tops among the clouds, and that no trees that drink water may reach up to them in height. For they are all given over to death, to the world below, among the children of man, with those who go down to the pit.' &ldquo;No trees by the waters may grow to towering height&rdquo; — the cedar's fall is a cosmic warning. All flesh is mortal (Isa 40:6). Christ alone was given what the cedar grasped: &ldquo;All authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me&rdquo; (Matt 28:18) — the authority the cedar seized, Christ received as gift from the Father.</p>",
    "15": "<p>A pattern: 'Thus says the Lord GOD: On the day it went down to Sheol I caused mourning; I covered the deep over it and restrained its rivers, and the many waters were stopped. I clothed Lebanon in gloom for it and all the trees of the field fainted because of it.' The whole natural order mourns the cedar's fall. Creation witnesses the event. This mourning of nature at the fall of the proud inverts the creation-mourning at the cross (darkness, earthquake, Matt 27:45, 51): at the cross, creation mourned the fall of the righteous one; here it mourns the fall of the proud one. The same natural signals carry opposite theological weights.</p>",
    "16": "<p>A direct revelation: 'I made the nations quake at the sound of its fall when I cast it down to Sheol with those who go down to the pit. And all the trees of Eden, the choice and best of Lebanon, all that drink water, were comforted in the world below.' The trees of Eden in Sheol are &ldquo;comforted&rdquo; — the previously fallen powers recognize the greatest empire has joined them. This is the anti-comfort of Sheol: the company of the dead does not console. The contrast with Christ's resurrection comfort is total: &ldquo;Blessed be the God and Father of our Lord Jesus Christ, the Father of mercies and God of all comfort&rdquo; (2 Cor 1:3). The comfort Christ gives is resurrection-comfort, not Sheol-comfort.</p>",
    "17": "<p>A structural note: 'They also went down to Sheol with it, to those who are slain by the sword; yes, those who were its arm, who lived under its shadow among the nations.' Those who sheltered in Egypt share its fate — they go down to Sheol with the cedar. The pattern is the anti-type of Christ's resurrection: those who are &ldquo;in Christ&rdquo; share his resurrection (1 Cor 15:22: &ldquo;as in Adam all die, so also in Christ shall all be made alive&rdquo;). Being in Egypt means sharing Egypt's Sheol-descent; being in Christ means sharing Christ's life.</p>",
    "18": "<p>A direct revelation: 'Whom are you thus like in glory and in greatness among the trees of Eden? You shall be brought down with the trees of Eden to the world below. You shall lie among the uncircumcised, with those who are slain by the sword. This is Pharaoh and all his multitude, declares the Lord GOD.' The oracle ends with Pharaoh identified as the great cedar. The contrast with Christ could not be more complete: Pharaoh goes down with the uncircumcised dead; Christ descends to the dead but rises, &ldquo;having the keys of Death and Hades&rdquo; (Rev 1:18). The one who goes down to Sheol in judgment goes down permanently; the one who descends in victory rises and reigns.</p>"
  },
  "32": {
    "1": "<p>A structural note: 'In the twelfth year in the twelfth month on the first day of the month the word of YHWH came to me.' March 585 BCE — fifteen months after Jerusalem's fall (July 586 BCE). The lament for Pharaoh begins after the destruction of Jerusalem is complete, suggesting that the Egypt-laments are the epilogue to Israel's judgment: YHWH's program of judgment has passed through his own people and now reaches their would-be savior. God judges his house first (1 Pet 4:17).</p>",
    "2": "<p>A type: 'Son of man, raise a lamentation over Pharaoh king of Egypt and say to him: You consider yourself a lion of the nations, but you are like a dragon in the seas; you burst forth in your rivers, trouble the waters with your feet, and foul their streams.' Pharaoh compares himself to a lion (<em>kefir goyim</em>) but YHWH compares him to a sea dragon (<em>tannin bayayamim</em>). The self-image and the divine diagnosis differ: Pharaoh sees royal majesty; YHWH sees primordial chaos. The dragon from the sea reappears in Revelation 13:1. Every human system that claims lion-majesty while being sea-dragon in its actual nature is Egypt-Pharaoh in new form. Christ alone is the true Lion (Rev 5:5: &ldquo;the Lion of the tribe of Judah has conquered&rdquo;) who is not secretly a dragon.</p>",
    "3": "<p>A pattern: 'Thus says the Lord GOD: I will throw my net over you with a host of many peoples and they will haul you up in my dragnet.' YHWH's net spread over the sea dragon — the sovereign fisher. Jesus's call of the disciples (Matt 4:19: &ldquo;I will make you fishers of men&rdquo;) recasts the fishing imagery in reverse: what was the net of judgment becomes the net of salvation. The same sovereign power that casts the net of judgment over the proud casts the gospel-net over the lost.</p>",
    "4": "<p>A structural note: 'And I will cast you on the ground; on the open field I will fling you and will cause all the birds of the heavens to settle on you and I will gorge the beasts of the whole earth with you.' Cast on the ground — the dragon of the sea brought to land and left exposed. The sea dragon out of its element: powerless, devoured. The same image of birds feasting on the fallen appears in Rev 19:17-18. Every manifestation of the beast-from-the-sea power ends in this same exposure and defeat.</p>",
    "5": "<p>A structural note: 'I will lay your flesh on the mountains and fill the valleys with your height.' The immensity of Egypt's fall — even its body fills mountains and valleys. The scale of the image corresponds to the scale of Egypt's former greatness: the empire that spread over continents is now reduced to a corpse that fills the landscape. Greatness in death becomes grotesque. The resurrection of Christ is the counter-image: the body glorified rather than scattered, raised rather than spread across mountains.</p>",
    "6": "<p>A structural note: 'I will drench the land even to the mountains with your flowing blood and the watercourses will be full of you.' Egypt's blood flooding the Nile: the water-to-blood motif from the Exodus plagues (Exod 7:17-21) is inverted. Egypt's own blood fills the rivers that Pharaoh claimed as his own (29:3). The river of death for Egypt's blood flows along the same path where the river of life will one day flow (Ezek 47:1-12; Rev 22:1).</p>",
    "7": "<p>A direct revelation: 'When I blot you out I will cover the heavens and make their stars dark; I will cover the sun with a cloud and the moon shall not give its light.' The darkening of the heavens at Egypt's fall is cosmic de-creation imagery: the celestial order worshipped in the solar cults of Heliopolis and Memphis goes dark. Jesus applies the same cosmic language to the parousia (Matt 24:29: &ldquo;the sun will be darkened and the moon will not give its light and the stars will fall&rdquo;). Every prophetic darkening of sky is a type of the last day when Christ appears and the old order gives way.</p>",
    "8": "<p>A direct revelation: 'All the bright lights of heaven will I make dark over you and put darkness on your land, declares the Lord GOD.' &ldquo;Put darkness on your land&rdquo; — the ninth plague of Egypt (Exod 10:21-23) comes full circle: the darkness that YHWH put on Egypt during the Exodus is replicated in Egypt's final judgment. And the darkness at the cross (Matt 27:45: &ldquo;from the sixth hour there was darkness over all the land&rdquo;) stands in the middle: the darkness at Golgotha is simultaneously a Passover-darkness (the true Passover lamb dying) and an Egypt-judgment darkness (the dragon finally judged). Christ on the cross is both the dying Lamb and the judged dragon-bearer.</p>",
    "9": "<p>A pattern: 'I will trouble the hearts of many peoples when I bring your destruction among the nations into the countries that you have not known.' The nations &ldquo;troubled in heart&rdquo; at Egypt's fall — the shock waves of imperial collapse reaching the edges of the known world. This disturbance among nations is one of the signs of the approaching Day of YHWH (Joel 3:9-16; Hag 2:7: &ldquo;I will shake all nations&rdquo;). The final shaking of the nations (Heb 12:26-27) accompanies the coming of the one who &ldquo;cannot be shaken&rdquo; — Christ and his unshakeable kingdom.</p>",
    "10": "<p>A structural note: 'I will make many peoples appalled at you and the hair of their kings shall bristle with horror because of you when I brandish my sword before them. They shall tremble every moment, every one for his own life, on the day of your downfall.' Every king appalled — the solidarity of rulers watching Egypt fall. What could happen to the greatest empire can happen to any. The existential dread (&ldquo;every one for his own life&rdquo;) is what awaits every power that has not submitted to Christ. The fear of the Lord that is the beginning of wisdom (Prov 9:10) is far better received before the judgment than in it.</p>",
    "11": "<p>A structural note: 'For thus says the Lord GOD: The sword of the king of Babylon shall come upon you.' Babylon as the sword of YHWH against Egypt — the same instrument YHWH used against Jerusalem. The Babylonian sword does not discriminate between YHWH's people and their enemies; both are cut by it in their appropriate season. The equal application of the divine instrument to both Israel and Egypt signals that YHWH's justice is impartial: &ldquo;judgment begins at the household of God&rdquo; (1 Pet 4:17) but does not stop there.</p>",
    "12": "<p>A structural note: 'By the swords of mighty ones I will cause your multitude to fall; they are all the most ruthless of nations. They shall bring to nothing the pride of Egypt and all its multitude shall perish.' The pride of Egypt (<em>gaon Mitsraim</em>) brought to nothing — pride specifically named as the target of YHWH's judgment. This is consistent throughout Ezekiel's oracle-against-nations section (28:2, 5, 17 for Tyre; 31:10 for the cedar): the sin that makes YHWH judge is always the pride that mistakes the creature for the Creator.</p>",
    "13": "<p>A structural note: 'I will destroy all its beasts from beside many waters; no foot of man shall trouble them anymore nor hoof of beast trouble them.' The silencing of Egypt — not just the people but the whole animal life of the land ceases. The agricultural and commercial ecosystem collapses. The absolute desolation signals cosmic un-creation, the reversal of the inhabiting of the land. Only the new creation (Rev 21-22) corrects this: where Egypt's land is emptied, the new earth is filled with life.</p>",
    "14": "<p>A structural note: 'Then I will let the waters of Egypt run clear and cause their rivers to run like oil, declares the Lord GOD.' After all feet have ceased the waters of Egypt run clear — the land returns to a pristine state through desolation. The clarity of waters through abandonment is a shadow of the water-of-life clarity in the new creation (Rev 22:1: &ldquo;clear as crystal&rdquo;). But Egypt's clarity is the emptiness of judgment; the new creation's clarity is the fullness of life.</p>",
    "15": "<p>A direct revelation: 'When I make the land of Egypt desolate and when the land is stripped of all that fills it, when I strike down all who dwell in it, then they will know that I am YHWH.' YHWH is known even in absolute emptiness — perhaps most clearly there, because all that previously crowded the vision of YHWH (the idols, the Pharaoh, the Nile, the empire) has been removed. The spiritual principle: when everything else is stripped away, YHWH is seen clearly. Paul learned this: &ldquo;I have learned, in whatever state I am, to be content&rdquo; (Phil 4:11) — stripping away every worldly support revealed Christ as all-sufficient.</p>",
    "16": "<p>A structural note: 'This is a lamentation that shall be chanted; the daughters of the nations shall chant it; over Egypt and all her multitude shall they chant it, declares the Lord GOD.' The lament is formalized as a text to be performed — the daughters of the nations as professional mourners chanting Ezekiel's oracle. The lament over Egypt is given literary permanence: it becomes part of the prophetic canon that all subsequent readers engage. The permanent record of divine judgment against the proud is embedded in Scripture for all time.</p>",
    "17": "<p>A structural note: 'In the twelfth year in the fifteenth day of the month the word of YHWH came to me.' March 585 BCE — two weeks after the first lament of chapter 32. The second lament over Egypt is addressed to Pharaoh's descent to Sheol. The double lament (32:1-16 and 32:17-32) is Ezekiel's most sustained meditation on death and the netherworld, surpassed in contrast only by the dry-bones vision (37:1-14).</p>",
    "18": "<p>A structural note: 'Son of man, wail over the multitude of Egypt and send them down, her and the daughters of majestic nations, to the world below, to those who have gone down to the pit.' The prophetic cry enacts the judgment it announces — the word of YHWH is performative, accomplishing what it declares (Isa 55:11). The same performative word that sends Egypt to the pit is the word that calls Lazarus from the tomb (John 11:43) and will call all the dead at the last trumpet (1 Cor 15:52).</p>",
    "19": "<p>A structural note: '&ldquo;Whom do you surpass in beauty? Go down and be laid to rest with the uncircumcised.&rdquo;' The mocking question — &ldquo;whom do you surpass in beauty?&rdquo; — echoes the cedar oracle's &ldquo;to which of the trees of Eden are you to be compared?&rdquo; (31:18). The answer is the same: nothing now. Go down. The descent to the pit is YHWH's final verdict on every claim to superior beauty and power. Christ's descent into the realm of the dead (1 Pet 3:18-20; Acts 2:27-28) is the total inversion: he goes down not under verdict but in victory, not to remain but to rise.</p>",
    "20": "<p>A pattern: 'They shall fall amid those who are slain by the sword. Egypt is delivered to the sword; drag her away and all her multitudes.' Fall among the slain — the great empire joins the nameless dead. The sword was Egypt's instrument of power; now it is Egypt's instrument of death. &ldquo;Those who live by the sword will die by the sword&rdquo; (Matt 26:52) — Egypt is the historical illustration of the principle Jesus names explicitly. The kingdom that advanced by the sword is ended by the sword.</p>",
    "21": "<p>A direct revelation: 'The mighty chiefs shall speak of them, with their helpers, out of the midst of Sheol: &ldquo;They have come down, they lie still, the uncircumcised, slain by the sword.&rdquo;' The mighty chiefs of Sheol speaking — the gathered dead of all nations recognizing Egypt's arrival. This is the &ldquo;Sheol-taunt&rdquo; form that appears in Isaiah 14 over Babylon: &ldquo;How you are fallen from heaven, O Lucifer!&rdquo; (Isa 14:12). When Christ arrives in the realm of the dead, it is as the herald of liberation, not as a fellow captive joining the assembly (1 Pet 3:18-20).</p>",
    "22": "<p>A structural note: 'Assyria is there and all her company, its graves all around it, all of them slain, fallen by the sword.' The roll call of nations in Sheol begins with Assyria — the great empire that preceded Babylon. Assyria had the same cedar-greatness (Ezek 31:3) and the same Sheol-destination. The vision of Sheol as populated by the fallen empires of history gives eschatological depth to the judgment. Daniel's vision of all the nations before the Ancient of Days (Dan 7:9-14) is the judicial counterpart to Ezekiel's vision of the nations in Sheol.</p>",
    "23": "<p>A structural note: 'Whose graves are set in the innermost parts of the pit and her company is all around her grave; all of them slain, fallen by the sword, who spread terror in the land of the living.' The innermost parts of the pit — the depths of Sheol — for those who spread the most terror. The measure of terror spread in life corresponds to the depth of descent in death. The eschatological reversal: in the new creation, those who were most humble in life are most exalted (Matt 5:3-11).</p>",
    "24": "<p>A structural note: 'Elam is there and all her multitude around her grave; all of them slain, fallen by the sword, who went down uncircumcised into the world below, who spread their terror in the land of the living; and they bear their shame with those who go down to the pit.' &ldquo;They bear their shame&rdquo;: shame persists in Sheol. The consciousness of shame in the realm of the dead is the OT's glimpse of what the NT calls eternal condemnation. Shame separated from Christ's covering (Rev 3:18: &ldquo;white garments so that the shame of your nakedness may not be seen&rdquo;) is permanent.</p>",
    "25": "<p>A structural note: 'They have made her a bed among the slain with all her multitude, her graves all around it, all of them uncircumcised, slain by the sword; for terror of them was spread in the land of the living, and they bear their shame with those who go down to the pit; they are placed among the slain.' The repeated phrase &ldquo;bear their shame with those who go down to the pit&rdquo; is Ezekiel's formula for those who die outside the covenant. In Sheol, that absence is permanent. The NT transposes this: those who die outside Christ bear their own shame; those who die in Christ are covered by his righteousness (2 Cor 5:21).</p>",
    "26": "<p>A structural note: 'Meshech-Tubal is there and all her multitude, her graves all around it, all of them uncircumcised, slain by the sword; for they spread their terror in the land of the living.' Meshech-Tubal — the distant northern peoples who will reappear in the Gog oracle (38:2-3) — are already in Sheol. Their Sheol-presence in chapter 32 and their appearance as the invading force in chapters 38-39 creates a canonical irony: the nations that Gog leads are the nations already judged. The final battle is against powers that are, in the deepest sense, already dead.</p>",
    "27": "<p>A pattern: 'And they do not lie with the mighty fallen of old who went down to Sheol with their weapons of war, whose swords were laid under their heads and whose shields are upon their bones; for the terror of the mighty was in the land of the living.' The &ldquo;mighty fallen of old&rdquo; buried with honor — weapons under their heads, shields as pillows — are distinguished from the dishonored nations. Even in Sheol, honor and dishonor persist. The ultimately decisive category is not warrior-honor but covenant: those who fall in YHWH's covenant are those who rise (Dan 12:2; 1 Thess 4:16).</p>",
    "28": "<p>A structural note: 'But as for you, you shall be broken and lie among the uncircumcised, with those who are slain by the sword.' Pharaoh explicitly placed among the uncircumcised — the supreme irony for a ruler whose land practiced circumcision as a ritual. In covenant terms, Pharaoh is classed with the pagans: not because of ritual but because of relationship. The NT expansion: &ldquo;For no one is a Jew who is merely one outwardly ... circumcision is a matter of the heart&rdquo; (Rom 2:28-29). True circumcision is of the heart — and Pharaoh's heart was never circumcised.</p>",
    "29": "<p>A structural note: 'Edom is there, her kings and all her princes, who for all their might are laid with those who are slain by the sword; they lie with the uncircumcised, with those who go down to the pit.' Edom — Israel's brother-nation (Gen 25:23-26) — is in Sheol with the uncircumcised. Despite Edom's kinship with Israel, its persistent hostility to YHWH's people put it in the class of the nations. Spiritual genealogy outweighs biological genealogy: the children of Abraham are those who share Abraham's faith (Gal 3:7), not merely his bloodline.</p>",
    "30": "<p>A structural note: 'The princes of the north are there, all of them, and all the Sidonians, who have gone down in shame with the slain, for all the terror that they caused by their might; they lie uncircumcised with those who are slain by the sword and bear their shame with those who go down to the pit.' North and south, east and west — the whole compass of ancient powers is represented in Sheol. This universality of the nations in Sheol corresponds to the universality of the resurrection from it: &ldquo;the sea gave up the dead who were in it, Death and Hades gave up the dead who were in them&rdquo; (Rev 20:13).</p>",
    "31": "<p>A direct revelation: 'When Pharaoh sees them he will be comforted for all his multitude, Pharaoh and all his army, slain by the sword, declares the Lord GOD.' Pharaoh is &ldquo;comforted&rdquo; to see all the other great powers in Sheol with him — the misery-loves-company comfort of the condemned. This is the anti-comfort of death: shared ruin rather than shared life. The resurrection-comfort Christ offers is the total inversion: shared life, shared resurrection, shared glory (John 17:22-24; Rom 8:17). The comfort of Sheol diminishes; the comfort of Christ's resurrection is eternal.</p>",
    "32": "<p>A direct revelation: 'For I spread my terror in the land of the living; and he shall be laid to rest among the uncircumcised, with those who are slain by the sword, Pharaoh and all his multitude, declares the Lord GOD.' The final word of the Egypt oracle: Pharaoh &ldquo;spread terror in the land of the living&rdquo; — his identity was terror-spreading — and he is laid with the uncircumcised dead. The contrast with Christ's final identity could not be greater: Christ spread life in the land of the living (&ldquo;I came that they may have life and have it abundantly,&rdquo; John 10:10) and was laid in a tomb from which he rose, now holding &ldquo;the keys of Death and Hades&rdquo; (Rev 1:18). Pharaoh goes down and stays down; Christ goes down and comes back up, making the way for all who are in him to follow.</p>"
  },
  "34": {
    "11": "<p>A direct revelation: 'For thus says the Lord GOD: Behold I, I myself will search for my sheep and seek them out ... I will rescue them from all places where they have been scattered ... I will seek the lost and I will bring back the strayed and I will bind up the injured and I will strengthen the weak.' Jesus's 'I am the good shepherd' (John 10:11) and the parable of the lost sheep (Luke 15:4-6) are the incarnational enactment of Ezek 34's promise. What YHWH said he himself would do (in contrast to the failed shepherds of Israel's leaders) is what Jesus does: the divine shepherd-promise is fulfilled by the Son who is YHWH present in person, doing what YHWH promised he personally would do for the scattered flock.</p>"
  },
  "36": {
    "27": "<p>A direct revelation: 'And I will put my Spirit within you and cause you to walk in my statutes and be careful to obey my rules.' Pentecost is Ezekiel 36:27 enacted. The Spirit's indwelling is not merely motivational but causally efficacious: 'I will cause you to walk' — the Hebrew Hiphil form makes YHWH the enabling cause of the obedience that follows. This is the new covenant's answer to the old covenant's demand without the enabling Spirit: the same Torah-standard now fulfilled because the Spirit from within enables what the law from without could only command. Paul's 'the righteous requirement of the law might be fulfilled in us who walk not according to the flesh but according to the Spirit' (Rom 8:4) is the Christological-pneumatological fulfillment of Ezek 36:27.</p>"
  },
  "47": {
    "9": "<p>A type: 'And wherever the river goes, every living creature that swarms will live, and there will be very many fish. For this water goes there, that the waters of the sea may become fresh; so everything will live where the river goes.' The eschatological temple-river of Ezekiel's vision (ch. 47), increasingly deep and life-giving, is the OT type for the water that flows from Christ. Jesus at Tabernacles (John 7:38-39) applies the Spirit-water promise to himself: 'rivers of living water will flow from within him' — and John explains this is the Spirit. Revelation's new creation river (22:1) flowing from the throne of God and the Lamb completes the Ezekiel type: the new temple's river is Christ himself, and all who drink from him live.</p>"
  }
}

